>Namaste friends,
>
>This is an age of growing populations and food shortages. A lot of 
>people are starving without food to eat. As those who can afford food 
>waste the limited food that is available, that jacks up food prices and 
>makes it even more inaccessible to starving people. This is already a 
>serious problem according to scientists and I am afraid will get much 
>worse in coming decades.
>
>Given this, wasting food is a really really really terrible sin in 
>today's times. Please don't waste food. This includes:
>
>(1) Cooking more food than you need and throwing it away,
>(2) Serving more food than you can eat in your plate and throwing it 
>away
>(3) Buying more vegetables/fruits than you need and letting them get 
>spoiled
>
>Please treat Mother Annapurna (personification of food that sustains us) 
>with respect, love and humility (rather than arrogance, contempt and 
>pride). World (and we) needs her blessings and kindness.
>
>*        *        *
>
>On a similar note, some ladies do rituals where chick peas soaked in 
>water, fruits etc, sweets etc are distributed to other ladies. I have 
>seen so many ladies casually get these food items, let them rot and then 
>throw them away. The notion that giving food to people is good karma is 
>based on the assumption that they actually eat it or use otherwise. If 
>they waste it, it is bad karma for both parties.
>
>Please do not accept any food that you cannot use. Also, don't 
>distribute food to people who do not need it. Instead, feed homeless, 
>needy people. Doing rituals with no common sense and just for the heck 
>of it, is not good. Such rituals produce no results whatsoever. Blindly 
>adhering to traditions that are doing no good really, is like dressing a 
>corpse in beautiful clothes and jewellery. Use common sense and do 
>*real* good to others and the world, than engaging in fake *symbols* 
>that in reality harm the world.
>
>Sorry for the strong language, but I do see many people abusing Mother 
>Annapoorna and I think this is terrible for the world. This needs to 
>change.
